President Obama met with members of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus to discuss the need for comprehensive immigration reform. He mentioned his upcoming speech on the topic and expressed his desire for a bipartisan approach based on the Senate proposal and the Schumer-Graham framework. The President highlighted the importance of securing borders and holding both illegal workers and employers accountable. He also emphasized the efforts his administration has made to secure borders, including requesting $600 million in supplemental appropriations and deploying additional National Guard forces. The President acknowledged that true border security requires comprehensive immigration reform and expressed his willingness to work with the CHC and Congress to take action as soon as possible. He thanked the CHC for their support in passing various bills, such as the economic recovery bill, healthcare reform, and education reform. The President also addressed the recent law passed in Arizona, stating that the Department of Justice was reviewing it.